HEADWORD: Recondite
<hw>Rec"on*dite</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧k"⟦ocr⟧n*d⟦imac⟧t ⟦or⟧
r⟦esl⟧k⟦ocr⟧n"d⟦icr⟧t; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>reconditus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>recondere</ets> to put up again, to
lay up, to conceal; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>condere</ets> to
bring or lay together. See <er>Abscond</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Hidden from the mental or intellectual view; secret; abstruse;
<as>as, <ex>recondite</ex> causes of things</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dealing in things abstruse; profound; searching;
<as>as, <ex>recondite</ex> studies</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Recondite</xex> learning.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp.
Horsley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reconditory</ent>⟦br⟧
